WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:08.008
[poignant music playing]

2
00:00:08.925 --> 00:00:10.965
[Charles] We have to have faith.
We have to believe.

3
00:00:11.011 --> 00:00:12.929
[Caroline] I don't know
how much longer I can.

4
00:00:13.013 --> 00:00:14.889
I don't know how much longer
I can believe.

5
00:00:14.973 --> 00:00:18.101
-We stayed because we couldn't go back.
-Maybe you can't go back.

6
00:00:18.184 --> 00:00:19.936
[Charles] Caroline. what does that mean?

7
00:00:24.149 --> 00:00:25.400
-[Caroline] Mary!
-[Laura] Mary?

8
00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:27.569
-[Charles] Mary?
-[Eliza] Caroline.

9
00:00:28.653 --> 00:00:29.653
Caroline.

10
00:00:31.614 --> 00:00:32.657
Caroline.

11
00:00:33.408 --> 00:00:34.284
[music fades]

12
00:00:34.367 --> 00:00:35.368
Eliza?

13
00:00:36.202 --> 00:00:37.245
Oh. goodness.

14
00:00:38.204 --> 00:00:40.498
Okay. let's get you up.

15
00:00:44.544 --> 00:00:45.587
[Caroline exhales]

16
00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:46.963
Oh.

17
00:00:47.047 --> 00:00:51.468
Nothing a little cake and tea won't fix.
Isn't that what Mother always said?

18
00:00:51.551 --> 00:00:52.927
[breathes deeply]

19
00:00:56.181 --> 00:01:00.185
We're down to the last crumbs
of maple sugar.

20
00:01:00.268 --> 00:01:01.394
Can you believe it?

21
00:01:02.437 --> 00:01:04.481
Peter can't go a day
without something sweet.

22
00:01:05.482 --> 00:01:09.027
-Now we'll have to rely on store-bought.
-What am I doing here?

23
00:01:10.111 --> 00:01:11.780
You came to your senses.

24
00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:13.406
[liquid pouring]

25
00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:14.491
What do you mean?

26
00:01:15.241 --> 00:01:17.243
[melancholy music playing]

27
00:01:19.079 --> 00:01:21.289
You know you're better off without him.

28
00:01:22.957 --> 00:01:25.126
You and the girls

29
00:01:25.627 --> 00:01:26.711
and the baby.

30
00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:32.133
I… I don't… [inhales sharply]

31
00:01:33.384 --> 00:01:34.511
When did I…

32
00:01:37.555 --> 00:01:38.640
[Charles] Caroline.

33
00:01:38.723 --> 00:01:39.974
[Caroline exhales]

34
00:01:40.058 --> 00:01:40.892
[Charles] Caroline.

35
00:01:40.975 --> 00:01:42.018
[breathes heavily]

36
00:01:42.811 --> 00:01:43.853
[Charles] Caroline.

37
00:01:43.937 --> 00:01:45.188
[Caroline] Hm.

38
00:01:45.271 --> 00:01:46.189
[music fades]

39
00:01:46.272 --> 00:01:48.733
-Hm.
-[Charles] You were talking in your sleep.

40
00:01:48.817 --> 00:01:51.069
[water dripping]

41
00:01:53.071 --> 00:01:55.073
[inhales] I'm fine.

42
00:01:57.283 --> 00:01:58.785
You can't still be mad?

43
00:01:59.577 --> 00:02:00.577
Try me.

44
00:02:03.998 --> 00:02:05.250
You have to drink.

45
00:02:06.501 --> 00:02:08.336
You always know best. don't you?

46
00:02:09.671 --> 00:02:11.256
Your words. not mine.

47
00:02:14.092 --> 00:02:16.261
-Where's Mary?
-She's cooler.

48
00:02:16.344 --> 00:02:18.221
-[birds chirping]
-[Caroline sighs]

49
00:02:18.304 --> 00:02:19.347
Laura's with her.

50
00:02:19.848 --> 00:02:20.848
[sighs]

51
00:02:20.890 --> 00:02:21.890
Good.

52
00:02:24.352 --> 00:02:25.478
[exhales sleepily]

53
00:02:25.562 --> 00:02:27.564
[tender music playing]

54
00:02:38.575 --> 00:02:39.868
[shivering]

55
00:02:39.951 --> 00:02:41.411
I'm so cold.

56
00:02:41.911 --> 00:02:44.706
-And I'm all shivery.
-[Laura] That's good.

57
00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:47.792
Pa says that means
the fever's coming down.

58
00:02:47.876 --> 00:02:52.589
But my bones still hurt.
and my mouth is all scratchy.

59
00:02:53.590 --> 00:02:54.590
Here you go.

60
00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:05.727
You rest. little lamb.

61
00:03:06.936 --> 00:03:08.605
You'll be better by morning.

62
00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:22.202
[indistinct chatter]

63
00:03:23.286 --> 00:03:25.288
[music fades]

64
00:03:25.914 --> 00:03:27.916
-[door opens]
-[bell jingles]

65
00:03:32.337 --> 00:03:34.217
[Emily] You look like
you haven't slept in days.

66
00:03:34.255 --> 00:03:35.089
I haven't.

67
00:03:35.173 --> 00:03:36.174
What's going on?

68
00:03:36.257 --> 00:03:39.510
Intermittent fever.
It's everywhere all of a sudden.

69
00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:43.431
So many newcomers are down.
and I'm already out of quinine.

70
00:03:44.307 --> 00:03:46.434
-Has your shipment come in?
-I'm sorry.

71
00:03:46.517 --> 00:03:47.517
[sighs in frustration]

72
00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:49.938
I put in the order two weeks ago.
but it hasn't come.

73
00:03:50.021 --> 00:03:52.301
I've got dozens more to see.
They're likely all suffering.

74
00:03:52.357 --> 00:03:53.691
I done need that quinine.

75
00:03:53.775 --> 00:03:56.152
Caleb. would you fetch my sandwich
from the back room?

76
00:03:58.196 --> 00:04:00.490
[footsteps receding]

77
00:04:00.573 --> 00:04:01.824
[door creaks]

78
00:04:01.908 --> 00:04:03.243
I've never seen it so bad.

79
00:04:03.326 --> 00:04:04.326
[door closes]

80
00:04:04.786 --> 00:04:05.787
Folks get the chills.

81
00:04:05.870 --> 00:04:09.666
and then their fever spikes.
and then the temperature drops down low.

82
00:04:09.749 --> 00:04:13.920
and they think it's over.
and then it starts up again twice as bad.

83
00:04:15.046 --> 00:04:17.382
-I might know where you can get some.
-Where?

84
00:04:17.465 --> 00:04:20.510
Jemma James ordered
a whole mess of it a few months ago.

85
00:04:21.219 --> 00:04:23.930
-Doubt she'll part with it though.
-Let me try.

86
00:04:24.013 --> 00:04:25.013
May I?

87
00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:30.228
[chuckles]

88
00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:33.730
Sharp.

89
00:04:35.358 --> 00:04:37.360
Now you're ready for battle.

90
00:04:37.443 --> 00:04:39.529
[footsteps approaching]

91
00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:43.490
Eat this.

92
00:04:44.325 --> 00:04:45.702
Take care of yourself.

93
00:04:46.619 --> 00:04:48.496
This town can't afford to lose you.

94
00:04:49.580 --> 00:04:51.124
[inhales deeply]

95
00:04:51.207 --> 00:04:52.458
I'll do my best.

96
00:04:55.169 --> 00:04:56.296
[footsteps receding]

97
00:04:56.379 --> 00:04:58.381
-[door opens]
-[bell jingles]

98
00:04:59.048 --> 00:05:00.133
[horses snuffling]

99
00:05:15.148 --> 00:05:16.274
For me?

100
00:05:16.858 --> 00:05:17.858
Really?

101
00:05:18.318 --> 00:05:21.571
People say coffee prevents a fever.
Can't hurt. right?

102
00:05:25.908 --> 00:05:27.160
[spits]

103
00:05:27.243 --> 00:05:28.077
[chuckles]

104
00:05:28.161 --> 00:05:30.580
It tastes like burned dirt.

105
00:05:30.663 --> 00:05:32.623
Well. I'm sorry we don't have any sugar.

106
00:05:32.707 --> 00:05:34.500
Just pretend
it's Grandpa's maple lemonade.

107
00:05:37.587 --> 00:05:39.756
Are you sure we don't need Dr. Tann?

108
00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:42.383
[Charles] Don't worry.
Fevers always run their course.

109
00:05:42.467 --> 00:05:46.387
When you and Mary were little.
you ran fevers all the time.

110
00:05:46.888 --> 00:05:48.598
Burnin' up like little stovepipes.

111
00:05:49.474 --> 00:05:52.727
Used to tell your ma. "Hey. Caroline.
we don't need wood tonight."

112
00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:55.980
"We'll let the girls lay in the fireplace
and heat the whole house."

113
00:05:56.064 --> 00:05:56.898
[Laura laughs]

114
00:05:56.981 --> 00:05:58.274
[Charles] Ma said no.

115
00:05:58.775 --> 00:06:02.653
You had to stay cozy in bed.
And Grandma tucked you in nice and tight.

116
00:06:02.737 --> 00:06:04.697
[emotional music playing]

117
00:06:04.781 --> 00:06:07.033
The Big Woods seem so far away now.

118
00:06:08.659 --> 00:06:12.455
I promise. if their fevers get higher
and they stop drinking water.

119
00:06:13.873 --> 00:06:15.666
that's when I'll ride out for Dr. Tann.

120
00:06:17.835 --> 00:06:20.421
Why don't you and Jack
run down the creek. get some water?

121
00:06:20.505 --> 00:06:22.065
Then I'll feed and water Pet and Patty.

122
00:06:25.343 --> 00:06:27.345
[horses neighing]

123
00:06:35.311 --> 00:06:36.604
[sighs]

124
00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:39.232
[fiddle music playing]

125
00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:43.653
[wind blowing]

126
00:06:45.863 --> 00:06:47.532
[unsettling music playing]

127
00:06:47.615 --> 00:06:49.617
[fiddle music continues]

128
00:06:52.954 --> 00:06:54.956
[fiddle music grows louder]

129
00:07:09.137 --> 00:07:11.347
You did some fine work here. Charlie.

130
00:07:12.807 --> 00:07:14.142
Some real fine work.

131
00:07:14.642 --> 00:07:15.768
George.

132
00:07:15.852 --> 00:07:20.273
Could this mantle be any more perfect?
You'd think we were born-and-bred masons.

133
00:07:20.356 --> 00:07:21.607
[George chuckles]

134
00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:25.611
And to think.
you didn't want me to come west with you.

135
00:07:26.904 --> 00:07:27.904
Turns out

136
00:07:28.865 --> 00:07:30.658
Kansas was exactly what I needed.

137
00:07:33.995 --> 00:07:34.829
[Laura] Pa?

138
00:07:34.912 --> 00:07:36.914
[wind whooshes softly]

139
00:07:39.083 --> 00:07:40.083
What's wrong?

140
00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:44.297
[sniffs]

141
00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:47.717
Help me into bed. Half Pint.

142
00:07:48.301 --> 00:07:49.301
[pail clangs]

143
00:07:50.303 --> 00:07:52.305
[Jack whines]

144
00:07:54.849 --> 00:07:58.394
I just need to close my eyes
and rest a minute. I'll be fine.

145
00:07:58.478 --> 00:08:00.897
[unsettling music continues]

146
00:08:01.898 --> 00:08:03.524
[Charles moans softly]

147
00:08:03.608 --> 00:08:04.650
[Charles groans]

148
00:08:06.527 --> 00:08:08.821
[Jack whines]

149
00:08:09.864 --> 00:08:13.075
[Laura] Don't worry. Jack.
He just needs to rest for a minute.

150
00:08:14.118 --> 00:08:15.786
I should get to the chores.

151
00:08:17.747 --> 00:08:19.749
[music fades]

152
00:08:22.168 --> 00:08:23.168
[knocking]

153
00:08:28.508 --> 00:08:30.885
Mrs. James. I'm glad to find you home.

154
00:08:30.968 --> 00:08:32.011
-How are ya?
-[Jemma] Uh…

155
00:08:32.094 --> 00:08:36.057
Very well. thank you.
What can I do for you. Dr. Tann?

156
00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:37.725
Well. I'm just checking on folks.

157
00:08:37.808 --> 00:08:40.186
And. uh. your family.
all healthy. I presume?

158
00:08:40.269 --> 00:08:43.356
-All thriving. thank you.
-Well. I'm glad to hear it.

159
00:08:43.439 --> 00:08:48.319
I'm sorry to report that it's not the same
for other families in the area.

160
00:08:48.402 --> 00:08:51.614
Intermittent fever has taken hold
in a very bad way.

161
00:08:51.697 --> 00:08:53.658
Dreadful disease.

162
00:08:54.909 --> 00:08:58.329
I understand that you're in possession
of a healthy stock of quinine.

163
00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:00.957
I do plan ahead. it's true.

164
00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:04.001
Perhaps you'd be generous enough
to loan me what you can spare?

165
00:09:04.085 --> 00:09:06.337
Just until the next shipment comes in.
of course.

166
00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:10.675
I'm afraid I can't spare any of it.
I've saved that quinine for emergencies.

167
00:09:10.758 --> 00:09:12.510
Oh. absolutely. I'd…

168
00:09:13.094 --> 00:09:14.762
I'd say this qualifies.

169
00:09:14.845 --> 00:09:17.848
especially for the new settlers
who have no experience

170
00:09:17.932 --> 00:09:20.101
with this… with this type of sickness.

171
00:09:20.184 --> 00:09:22.144
Family emergencies.

172
00:09:23.437 --> 00:09:25.273
I'd be happy to purchase it from you.

173
00:09:26.399 --> 00:09:30.027
-At least a down payment.
-It's not about the money.

174
00:09:30.111 --> 00:09:31.028
Oh. no. of course not.

175
00:09:31.112 --> 00:09:35.866
I appreciate everything that you're doing.
but I'm afraid I just can't help.

176
00:09:38.494 --> 00:09:39.495
[Jemma gasps softly]

177
00:09:40.788 --> 00:09:42.164
Without quinine.

178
00:09:43.499 --> 00:09:44.499
people will die.

179
00:09:44.542 --> 00:09:45.585
[tense music playing]

180
00:09:45.668 --> 00:09:49.297
And it wouldn't be right
to allow my own to be listed among them.

181
00:09:59.223 --> 00:10:01.225
[melancholy music playing]

182
00:10:09.984 --> 00:10:12.194
[horse snorts]

183
00:10:17.617 --> 00:10:19.702
[grunts. sighs]

184
00:10:40.973 --> 00:10:42.058
[Caroline] Laura?

185
00:10:43.225 --> 00:10:45.061
Mary. where are you?

186
00:10:45.561 --> 00:10:47.146
[horse whinnies]

187
00:10:49.023 --> 00:10:50.024
[exhales]

188
00:10:51.651 --> 00:10:52.651
Laura?

189
00:10:52.693 --> 00:10:54.320
[music continues]

190
00:10:54.403 --> 00:10:55.403
Mary?

191
00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:16.258
Oh. there you are.
Everyone's excited to see you tonight.

192
00:11:16.342 --> 00:11:19.095
so I thought we'd find you
something to wear.

193
00:11:22.473 --> 00:11:23.766
Where are the girls?

194
00:11:26.394 --> 00:11:27.728
School. of course.

195
00:11:30.147 --> 00:11:33.734
These dresses are worn to threads.

196
00:11:34.568 --> 00:11:35.903
[sighs heavily]

197
00:11:35.986 --> 00:11:38.239
What did he have you doing out there?

198
00:11:40.116 --> 00:11:42.326
[Caroline inhales shakily]
I met Charles in that dress.

199
00:11:43.327 --> 00:11:44.327
[Eliza gasps]

200
00:11:45.538 --> 00:11:47.039
Do you remember this one?

201
00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:51.043
You wore it at the Walton wedding.

202
00:11:51.127 --> 00:11:52.127
[inhales sharply]

203
00:11:52.169 --> 00:11:55.423
Robert Benton couldn't resist you
in this dress.

204
00:11:55.506 --> 00:11:59.844
[inhales deeply] He was wealthy
and kind and dependable.

205
00:12:00.469 --> 00:12:02.906
He certainly wouldn't have dragged you
to the end of the earth

206
00:12:02.930 --> 00:12:04.181
while expecting a child.

207
00:12:06.475 --> 00:12:07.977
[sighs]

208
00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:09.854
You know this is for the best.

209
00:12:12.773 --> 00:12:14.442
-I do.
-[Eliza] Here.

210
00:12:14.525 --> 00:12:15.860
[unsettling music playing]

211
00:12:20.865 --> 00:12:21.782
[gasps softly]

212
00:12:21.866 --> 00:12:23.576
-You have to drink.
-[music ends]

213
00:12:25.703 --> 00:12:27.455
[birds chirping]

214
00:12:27.538 --> 00:12:29.248
[Laura] He's just resting a minute.

215
00:12:29.331 --> 00:12:32.418
[Caroline exhales]

216
00:12:33.002 --> 00:12:34.295
He's so hot.

217
00:12:35.045 --> 00:12:37.590
Pa says you have to drink.

218
00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:42.136
[groans]

219
00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:44.430
[breathes shakily]

220
00:12:48.309 --> 00:12:49.477
[sighs]

221
00:12:52.897 --> 00:12:55.691
-What about you? How are you feeling?
-[Laura] I'm fine.

222
00:12:56.609 --> 00:12:58.110
I've been doing chores.

223
00:12:58.194 --> 00:12:59.820
Don't wear yourself out.

224
00:13:00.321 --> 00:13:02.156
I won't. I promise.

225
00:13:03.324 --> 00:13:05.743
[tender music playing]

226
00:13:29.308 --> 00:13:31.310
[music continues]

227
00:13:44.824 --> 00:13:46.826
[Jack whimpering]

228
00:13:52.873 --> 00:13:54.875
[upbeat music playing]

229
00:14:02.049 --> 00:14:03.175
That should do it.

230
00:14:05.427 --> 00:14:06.554
[exhales]

231
00:14:06.637 --> 00:14:07.805
[cup scrapes]

232
00:14:10.432 --> 00:14:11.976
[music fades]

233
00:14:12.059 --> 00:14:13.978
-[knocking on door]
-Come in!

234
00:14:15.688 --> 00:14:18.023
Emily tells me you're out of quinine.

235
00:14:18.107 --> 00:14:20.401
I'm looking for anything else
I can use to treat symptoms.

236
00:14:20.484 --> 00:14:23.904
-Snakeroot. rhubarb. castor oil…
-[Lacey] What. uh... Let me help.

237
00:14:23.988 --> 00:14:26.699
I have a stash back at the house.
You're welcome to it.

238
00:14:26.782 --> 00:14:28.742
Quinine? How?

239
00:14:28.826 --> 00:14:31.996
Someone's loss is our gain.
Do you want to ride out with me?

240
00:14:32.872 --> 00:14:33.872
Lead the way.

241
00:14:36.709 --> 00:14:38.711
[birds chirping]

242
00:14:39.712 --> 00:14:40.880
[Laura] Pa.

243
00:14:41.547 --> 00:14:42.756
time for a drink.

244
00:14:43.507 --> 00:14:44.633
[Charles] Hm.

245
00:14:49.179 --> 00:14:50.347
[breathes shakily]

246
00:14:50.431 --> 00:14:52.433
[tense music playing]

247
00:14:56.645 --> 00:14:58.939
Ma. wake up. It's time for a drink.

248
00:15:01.984 --> 00:15:02.985
[Laura gasps]

249
00:15:06.196 --> 00:15:07.990
Why are they so hot again?

250
00:15:11.577 --> 00:15:12.577
Mary.

251
00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:15.831
Mm.

252
00:15:21.086 --> 00:15:22.087
[Mary grunts]

253
00:15:23.339 --> 00:15:26.467
-Jack and I are going for help.
-What?

254
00:15:29.136 --> 00:15:32.681
Ma and Pa are hot as fire.
and they won't drink any water.

255
00:15:33.265 --> 00:15:36.685
-I have to saddle up Pet and get Dr. Tann.
-[Mary] But you can't.

256
00:15:36.769 --> 00:15:40.314
-You've never ridden alone before.
-[Laura] It's fine. Pet knows the way.

257
00:15:40.898 --> 00:15:42.107
I'll be back soon.

258
00:15:43.067 --> 00:15:44.234
I promise.

259
00:15:45.152 --> 00:15:47.321
[tense strings music playing]

260
00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:57.498
[Jack whining]

261
00:16:04.129 --> 00:16:05.129
Pet?

262
00:16:05.756 --> 00:16:06.756
Patty?

263
00:16:08.384 --> 00:16:10.469
Pet! Patty!

264
00:16:22.272 --> 00:16:23.565
[Jack barking]

265
00:16:23.649 --> 00:16:24.566
[music ends]

266
00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:26.652
[hammering on wood]

267
00:16:27.861 --> 00:16:29.571
[hammering continues]

268
00:16:29.655 --> 00:16:31.198
[birds singing]

269
00:16:33.826 --> 00:16:36.704
[hammering resumes]

270
00:16:46.922 --> 00:16:49.466
[rustling]

271
00:16:51.969 --> 00:16:54.263
You waiting on an engraved invitation?

272
00:16:54.346 --> 00:16:55.723
[wood thuds]

273
00:16:58.183 --> 00:16:59.184
[sighs]

274
00:17:02.896 --> 00:17:03.896
[man grunts]

275
00:17:05.024 --> 00:17:07.651
When do you plan
on setting out for the West?

276
00:17:08.235 --> 00:17:09.278
Early spring.

277
00:17:10.988 --> 00:17:12.322
Before the lake thaws.

278
00:17:13.449 --> 00:17:16.452
Your brother won't stop
rambling on about it.

279
00:17:18.162 --> 00:17:23.333
He spent every penny he had
on dime novels and a coonskin cap.

280
00:17:23.417 --> 00:17:25.961
Thinks he's gonna be Davy Crockett.

281
00:17:26.045 --> 00:17:27.087
Right.

282
00:17:32.009 --> 00:17:33.009
About that…

283
00:17:37.097 --> 00:17:38.640
Well. spit it out.

284
00:17:41.977 --> 00:17:43.645
I can't take George with me.

285
00:17:45.606 --> 00:17:47.066
Well. he'll be disappointed.

286
00:17:47.691 --> 00:17:50.194
If that's your decision.
he's welcome to stay home with us.

287
00:17:50.277 --> 00:17:52.404
-He can't stay here either.
-Oh. he can't. can't he?

288
00:17:52.988 --> 00:17:54.239
[wood thuds]

289
00:17:55.115 --> 00:17:59.661
He's not right in the head. Father.
You know he isn't. not since the war.

290
00:17:59.745 --> 00:18:01.246
Don't be ridiculous.

291
00:18:01.830 --> 00:18:03.082
He wears a tattered uniform

292
00:18:03.165 --> 00:18:06.126
that's two sizes too small.
sees soldiers that aren't there.

293
00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:08.212
He wakes up screaming every night.

294
00:18:08.295 --> 00:18:10.756
All he needs is something
to keep himself occupied.

295
00:18:10.839 --> 00:18:12.549
and you were gonna give him that.

296
00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:17.137
I talked to some people about a place
in Pennsylvania. treats soldiers like him.

297
00:18:17.221 --> 00:18:20.057
You talked to people about George?

298
00:18:20.641 --> 00:18:23.936
-I wanna take him there before I set off.
-He's not sick!

299
00:18:24.019 --> 00:18:25.437
He's a hero.

300
00:18:26.271 --> 00:18:27.815
All heroes have scars.

301
00:18:27.898 --> 00:18:30.275
but you wouldn't know
anything about that. would you?

302
00:18:30.359 --> 00:18:32.820
He needs help from people
who know how to help him.

303
00:18:33.362 --> 00:18:35.482
George is broken.
and someone needs to put him back...

304
00:18:35.531 --> 00:18:36.824
[rustling]

305
00:18:36.907 --> 00:18:38.909
[morose music playing]

306
00:18:39.785 --> 00:18:40.786
[Charles] George!

307
00:18:41.787 --> 00:18:42.787
George. wait!

308
00:18:44.873 --> 00:18:48.210
George! George. come back! I'm sorry!

309
00:18:51.046 --> 00:18:52.046
George!

310
00:18:56.093 --> 00:19:00.013
[breathing heavily]

311
00:19:01.473 --> 00:19:03.475
[music fades]

312
00:19:03.559 --> 00:19:04.977
[birds chirping]

313
00:19:05.060 --> 00:19:07.020
[Jack panting]

314
00:19:13.861 --> 00:19:15.779
-[Jack barks]
-[horse whinnies]

315
00:19:18.115 --> 00:19:19.283
[Jack barks]

316
00:19:22.035 --> 00:19:23.829
-Sit. Stay.
-[Jack whimpers]

317
00:19:25.747 --> 00:19:27.249
[knocking on door]

318
00:19:28.375 --> 00:19:31.128
Hello? Is anyone home?

319
00:19:31.211 --> 00:19:33.255
[chickens clucking]

320
00:19:35.591 --> 00:19:37.593
[somber music playing]

321
00:19:45.225 --> 00:19:46.518
Mrs. Mitchell?

322
00:19:49.438 --> 00:19:50.647
Mr. Mitchell?

323
00:20:06.205 --> 00:20:08.290
[kitten meowing]

324
00:20:15.172 --> 00:20:17.174
[kittens continue meowing]

325
00:20:30.604 --> 00:20:34.149
[White Sun in Osage] Is that you. Julia?

326
00:20:42.532 --> 00:20:43.575
[in English] Julia…

327
00:20:44.076 --> 00:20:45.076
[Laura] No.

328
00:20:45.577 --> 00:20:47.371
It's me. It's Laura Ingalls.

329
00:20:47.913 --> 00:20:49.790
[White Sun moans]

330
00:20:49.873 --> 00:20:50.999
Who's with you?

331
00:20:51.833 --> 00:20:52.833
[Laura] No one.

332
00:20:53.627 --> 00:20:54.753
Just my dog Jack.

333
00:20:56.171 --> 00:20:58.715
My family has the fever.
and our horses are missing.

334
00:20:58.799 --> 00:21:00.175
[moans softly]

335
00:21:00.259 --> 00:21:03.679
I was hoping Mr. Mitchell
could take me to get Dr. Tann.

336
00:21:03.762 --> 00:21:06.515
William went out of town for work.

337
00:21:07.557 --> 00:21:09.101
He won't be back for days. [shivering]

338
00:21:10.477 --> 00:21:12.396
[White Sun moans]

339
00:21:12.479 --> 00:21:13.479
Oh.

340
00:21:15.065 --> 00:21:17.609
[Good Eagle in Osage] Mama?
I need more water.

341
00:21:19.194 --> 00:21:20.445
[in English] I'll do it.

342
00:21:20.529 --> 00:21:21.571
[Good Eagle grunts]

343
00:21:21.655 --> 00:21:22.823
[White Sun grunts]

344
00:21:31.206 --> 00:21:34.334
[Good Eagle gasping]

345
00:21:35.127 --> 00:21:37.129
[Good Eagle gulping]

346
00:21:39.131 --> 00:21:40.966
[moans]

347
00:21:44.928 --> 00:21:46.221
[groans]

348
00:21:49.766 --> 00:21:51.143
[water pouring]

349
00:21:54.479 --> 00:21:55.939
[gulping]

350
00:21:56.023 --> 00:21:57.274
[exhales]

351
00:21:59.901 --> 00:22:02.195
I could keep going to town.

352
00:22:02.904 --> 00:22:04.573
No. not alone.

353
00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:07.701
-[Laura] I won't be alone. I'll have Jack.
-Hm.

354
00:22:07.784 --> 00:22:10.412
I'm a fast runner. Don't worry.

355
00:22:12.456 --> 00:22:14.458
[Good Eagle whimpers]

356
00:22:17.544 --> 00:22:19.504
Do you know how
to get to the main road from here?

357
00:22:20.088 --> 00:22:21.423
I think so.

358
00:22:22.174 --> 00:22:23.467
[groans]

359
00:22:23.550 --> 00:22:25.344
[poignant music playing]

360
00:22:25.427 --> 00:22:28.347
Follow it east straight to town.

361
00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:29.306
[breathing heavily]

362
00:22:29.389 --> 00:22:30.932
Wave down anyone you see.

363
00:22:32.809 --> 00:22:35.520
But don't leave the road for any reason.

364
00:22:35.604 --> 00:22:36.897
Promise me?

365
00:22:37.939 --> 00:22:39.066
I promise.

366
00:22:42.861 --> 00:22:44.237
[breathing heavily]

367
00:22:44.321 --> 00:22:45.447
[in Osage] God.

368
00:22:46.531 --> 00:22:51.161
Help Laura on her journey.

369
00:22:51.244 --> 00:22:55.665
That the enemy nor a creature

370
00:22:56.249 --> 00:22:57.501
will harm her.

371
00:23:01.963 --> 00:23:03.173
[White Sun gasps]

372
00:23:10.305 --> 00:23:11.640
[music fades]

373
00:23:14.726 --> 00:23:15.726
[in English] Caleb?

374
00:23:18.105 --> 00:23:19.648
[door closes]

375
00:23:24.152 --> 00:23:26.613
Where are you goin'
with ginger root and willow bark?

376
00:23:27.906 --> 00:23:28.906
The Ingalls'.

377
00:23:29.366 --> 00:23:32.452
They're late picking up their package.
and I'm… I'm afraid they got the fever.

378
00:23:32.536 --> 00:23:34.663
[Emily] If they have.
there's nothing you can do.

379
00:23:34.746 --> 00:23:37.916
They need quinine. We won't have any
till Dr. Tann and Lacey come back.

380
00:23:37.999 --> 00:23:40.710
-I just wanna check on them.
-Caleb. I don't want you getting sick.

381
00:23:40.794 --> 00:23:43.505
But Dr. Tann did say you can't catch
the fever from other people.

382
00:23:43.588 --> 00:23:48.468
No one… no one knows how you catch it.
not even Dr. Tann.

383
00:23:48.552 --> 00:23:50.345
And I won't have you taking the chance.

384
00:23:50.429 --> 00:23:53.390
Dr. Tann and Lacey plan
to visit all the families west of town.

385
00:23:53.473 --> 00:23:55.976
I'm sure the Ingalls
will be first on the list.

386
00:23:56.059 --> 00:23:57.894
All right? Just have some faith. Caleb.

387
00:23:59.020 --> 00:24:00.147
Yes. ma'am.

388
00:24:04.151 --> 00:24:05.694
[horse whinnies]

389
00:24:08.738 --> 00:24:09.738
[scoffs]

390
00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:13.952
Okay. Finish sweeping up.
I'll make you something to eat.

391
00:24:19.124 --> 00:24:20.959
[sweeping]

392
00:24:22.085 --> 00:24:23.795
[hopeful music playing]

393
00:24:32.679 --> 00:24:34.264
[Jack barking]

394
00:24:38.727 --> 00:24:39.727
[Laura] Jack!

395
00:24:40.228 --> 00:24:41.228
Jack.

396
00:24:42.898 --> 00:24:43.899
Look.

397
00:24:43.982 --> 00:24:47.777
Hello! Hello! Hello!

398
00:24:48.278 --> 00:24:50.697
Please! We need help!

399
00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:52.782
[Jack barking]

400
00:25:02.584 --> 00:25:04.503
[music intensifies. calms]

401
00:25:08.465 --> 00:25:09.549
Grandma?

402
00:25:10.842 --> 00:25:13.178
[both laugh excitedly]

403
00:25:13.261 --> 00:25:14.971
What are you doing in Kansas?

404
00:25:15.055 --> 00:25:16.723
I missed my girls.

405
00:25:17.307 --> 00:25:18.683
-[Laura] I missed you too.
-Oh…

406
00:25:20.602 --> 00:25:22.896
-Everyone's sick with a fever.
-[Grandma] Hm.

407
00:25:22.979 --> 00:25:24.481
-I have to get the doctor.
-Hm.

408
00:25:25.482 --> 00:25:27.150
I'm all right. I'm just hot.

409
00:25:28.652 --> 00:25:33.532
Well. come on. then. Let's get to town.
You can tell me everything on the way.

410
00:25:33.615 --> 00:25:36.409
-How do you like living on the prairie?
-[Laura] I like it.

411
00:25:36.493 --> 00:25:37.869
[Grandma] Hm.

412
00:25:38.620 --> 00:25:42.123
I made you and Mary
a tea set for the playhouse.

413
00:25:42.624 --> 00:25:44.501
You're not too old for tea sets. are you?

414
00:25:45.001 --> 00:25:46.836
-We're not too old.
-[sighs in relief] Good.

415
00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:49.756
[chuckles] Because I can't wait
to show you.

416
00:25:49.839 --> 00:25:50.840
[sighs]

417
00:25:51.883 --> 00:25:53.301
We should be there soon.

418
00:25:55.178 --> 00:25:57.180
[Jack barks distantly]

419
00:25:58.139 --> 00:26:00.016
-Quiet. Jack.
-[Jack barks distantly]

420
00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:02.018
[Jack barking]

421
00:26:03.019 --> 00:26:04.688
[Jack whining and barking]

422
00:26:06.565 --> 00:26:08.233
[Jack continues barking]

423
00:26:08.316 --> 00:26:11.236
[music crescendoes. fades]

424
00:26:11.319 --> 00:26:13.321
[birds chirping]

425
00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:23.080
Pa?

426
00:26:35.635 --> 00:26:36.469
Pa?

427
00:26:36.553 --> 00:26:38.138
[poignant music playing]

428
00:26:38.221 --> 00:26:39.347
[sniffs]

429
00:26:41.182 --> 00:26:42.182
[Mary] Pa!

430
00:26:42.642 --> 00:26:43.642
[Charles] George!

431
00:26:44.227 --> 00:26:45.645
Hey. you don't have to go. You…

432
00:26:46.146 --> 00:26:48.982
You don't have to do
anything you don't wanna do.

433
00:26:49.065 --> 00:26:52.485
[breathes heavily]

434
00:26:52.569 --> 00:26:53.945
[exhales]

435
00:26:56.865 --> 00:26:59.284
[inhales shakily]

436
00:27:02.287 --> 00:27:03.455
[gasps]

437
00:27:08.293 --> 00:27:10.337
[inhales sharply. gasps]

438
00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:12.839
[father] Why couldn't you
leave well enough alone?

439
00:27:15.008 --> 00:27:16.088
[Charles] I wanted to help.

440
00:27:19.179 --> 00:27:21.473
You always think you know best.

441
00:27:21.556 --> 00:27:23.183
I… I'm sorry.

442
00:27:24.768 --> 00:27:26.770
I'll never forgive you for this.

443
00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:35.362
I'm sorry!

444
00:27:37.113 --> 00:27:38.113
Please!

445
00:27:39.282 --> 00:27:40.283
Father!

446
00:27:46.915 --> 00:27:48.291
Father. come back!

447
00:27:50.752 --> 00:27:51.961
I'm sorry!

448
00:27:52.045 --> 00:27:54.047
[music builds]

449
00:27:55.757 --> 00:27:56.757
[Mary] Pa?

450
00:27:57.509 --> 00:27:58.677
[music fades]

451
00:27:58.760 --> 00:28:01.554
Pa. wake up. Pa?

452
00:28:01.638 --> 00:28:02.638
[Mary gasps]

453
00:28:02.681 --> 00:28:04.557
[inhales shakily] Mary.

454
00:28:08.144 --> 00:28:10.021
You went walking in your sleep?

455
00:28:12.315 --> 00:28:13.441
[Mary sobs]

456
00:28:13.525 --> 00:28:16.403
-I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
-[Mary continues sobbing]

457
00:28:20.281 --> 00:28:21.741
Who were you talking to?

458
00:28:22.242 --> 00:28:23.076
[Charles] No one.

459
00:28:23.159 --> 00:28:24.452
It doesn't matter.

460
00:28:25.453 --> 00:28:27.914
-[Mary sobs]
-[Charles breathes heavily]

461
00:28:27.997 --> 00:28:29.207
[horse neighing]

462
00:28:29.290 --> 00:28:31.126
[poignant music playing]

463
00:28:31.209 --> 00:28:32.252
Dr. Tann!

464
00:28:37.716 --> 00:28:39.467
[horses whinnying]

465
00:28:44.639 --> 00:28:45.765
[Mary] He has the fever.

466
00:28:45.849 --> 00:28:48.560
-We all have the fever.
-[Dr. Tann] Hey. Whoa. Whoa. Whoa.

467
00:28:48.643 --> 00:28:51.354
Okay. All right. You're all right.

468
00:28:52.105 --> 00:28:54.524
Drink this up. Drink it all up.

469
00:28:55.734 --> 00:28:57.454
-[Dr. Tann] Here you go.
-[Lacey] That's it.

470
00:28:58.027 --> 00:28:58.862
[Mary gasps]

471
00:28:58.945 --> 00:29:02.282
-Aren't you a brave little bunny?
-Let's get you two back up to the house.

472
00:29:03.324 --> 00:29:04.492
Is Laura with you?

473
00:29:05.326 --> 00:29:07.579
Laura? Why would she be with me?

474
00:29:08.288 --> 00:29:09.998
She rode off to get Dr. Tann

475
00:29:11.124 --> 00:29:12.125
hours ago.

476
00:29:14.919 --> 00:29:15.919
[Mary exhales]

477
00:29:16.421 --> 00:29:17.630
[birds chirping]

478
00:29:22.510 --> 00:29:24.512
[Jack barking]

479
00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:29.517
[Jack whines. barks]

480
00:29:32.353 --> 00:29:34.773
[Jack panting]

481
00:29:35.356 --> 00:29:36.941
Where did Grandma go?

482
00:29:40.195 --> 00:29:43.448
[Caleb] Hey. Good boy. Jack.
Good boy. All right.

483
00:29:44.574 --> 00:29:45.658
Here. Here.

484
00:29:46.242 --> 00:29:47.535
[Jack whines]

485
00:29:49.996 --> 00:29:50.996
[Caleb] Here.

486
00:29:51.414 --> 00:29:54.083
It's okay. Just here. Yeah.

487
00:29:59.005 --> 00:30:00.632
Do you think you can stand?

488
00:30:01.299 --> 00:30:02.967
Yeah. you think so? Okay.

489
00:30:03.468 --> 00:30:04.719
[Caleb grunts]

490
00:30:05.303 --> 00:30:06.303
All right.

491
00:30:08.181 --> 00:30:10.892
Don't worry. I'll get you somewhere safe.

492
00:30:11.476 --> 00:30:12.519
[Jack barking]

493
00:30:18.650 --> 00:30:19.650
[music fades]

494
00:30:20.568 --> 00:30:22.737
[groans]

495
00:30:22.821 --> 00:30:24.322
[doorknob rattles]

496
00:30:24.405 --> 00:30:26.324
[grunts. exhales]

497
00:30:26.407 --> 00:30:28.868
-[door opens]
-[sighs]

498
00:30:28.952 --> 00:30:30.954
[tense music playing]

499
00:30:37.335 --> 00:30:39.546
I thought we agreed on the yellow.

500
00:30:40.129 --> 00:30:41.506
I didn't want the yellow.

501
00:30:42.715 --> 00:30:44.092
Don't be ridiculous.

502
00:30:46.094 --> 00:30:48.096
Robert is expecting you at dinner.

503
00:30:48.179 --> 00:30:50.473
You still have a chance
at that life. Caroline.

504
00:30:51.474 --> 00:30:53.059
I didn't want that life.

505
00:30:55.603 --> 00:30:58.523
Robert was dull and predictable.

506
00:30:59.566 --> 00:31:00.733
He was safe.

507
00:31:02.485 --> 00:31:03.987
I wanted something different.

508
00:31:04.737 --> 00:31:06.155
Charles lied to you.

509
00:31:06.656 --> 00:31:07.657
[inhales deeply]

510
00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:10.034
He's overly optimistic and naive.

511
00:31:11.870 --> 00:31:13.621
But he's also brilliant…

512
00:31:13.705 --> 00:31:15.081
[hopeful music playing]

513
00:31:15.164 --> 00:31:16.583
…and inventive

514
00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:22.297
and driven by love
and hope and a sense of adventure.

515
00:31:24.382 --> 00:31:26.384
And I always wanted that for my life.

516
00:31:29.220 --> 00:31:32.015
I always imagined
I was that kind of person too.

517
00:31:32.849 --> 00:31:35.894
He makes me feel whole. Eliza.

518
00:31:38.646 --> 00:31:40.732
He makes me feel like myself.

519
00:31:44.110 --> 00:31:46.070
You've never understood that.

520
00:31:49.324 --> 00:31:50.825
This is what you want?

521
00:31:52.952 --> 00:31:54.621
An uncertain life?

522
00:31:57.206 --> 00:32:00.126
An uncertain life
is full of possibilities.

523
00:32:02.003 --> 00:32:04.422
I want a life full of possibilities.

524
00:32:07.216 --> 00:32:08.843
You're all alone out there.

525
00:32:11.262 --> 00:32:12.513
I don't think we are.

526
00:32:19.228 --> 00:32:20.605
[doorknob rattles]

527
00:32:20.688 --> 00:32:22.315
[sighs]

528
00:32:22.398 --> 00:32:23.398
[grunts]

529
00:32:25.860 --> 00:32:27.362
Let me go home. Eliza.

530
00:32:27.862 --> 00:32:29.697
I'm not the one keeping you here.

531
00:32:29.781 --> 00:32:31.783
[ominous music playing]

532
00:32:34.953 --> 00:32:36.871
[music fades]

533
00:32:42.126 --> 00:32:43.169
Welcome back.

534
00:32:47.465 --> 00:32:50.468
Charles is outside. um.
taking some fresh air.

535
00:32:50.551 --> 00:32:53.429
Mary is resting.
and Laura is at the Mitchells' house.

536
00:32:53.513 --> 00:32:56.182
Why? What… what is she doing there?

537
00:32:56.265 --> 00:33:00.603
Well. she went looking for help.
and she fell ill near the homestead.

538
00:33:00.687 --> 00:33:03.272
But Caleb found her and brought her back.

539
00:33:04.357 --> 00:33:05.692
She's absolutely fine.

540
00:33:05.775 --> 00:33:09.946
Dr. Tann said he's never seen
two convalescing girls have so much fun.

541
00:33:11.364 --> 00:33:15.451
Broth. It'll take that taste
of quinine out of your mouth

542
00:33:15.535 --> 00:33:18.997
and… put a little meat on your bones.

543
00:33:21.541 --> 00:33:23.459
Thank you for taking care of us.

544
00:33:24.544 --> 00:33:26.629
I… I hope you'll let me make it up to you.

545
00:33:26.713 --> 00:33:27.630
Ah.

546
00:33:27.714 --> 00:33:30.341
There's no need. It's my pleasure.

547
00:33:30.967 --> 00:33:35.054
And. um. Mr. Edwards. is… is he well?

548
00:33:36.180 --> 00:33:37.515
He had just a touch.

549
00:33:38.016 --> 00:33:39.851
[birds chirping]

550
00:33:41.060 --> 00:33:44.605
John was the one who rode
for the quinine a few weeks ago.

551
00:33:45.356 --> 00:33:47.817
He used every last penny of his winnings.

552
00:33:49.736 --> 00:33:52.822
He had a feeling
that people would be hurting.

553
00:33:52.905 --> 00:33:55.408
And he cannot stand to see people hurting.

554
00:33:57.076 --> 00:33:58.578
Please send him my gratitude.

555
00:34:01.998 --> 00:34:05.293
I'm gonna go check on Mary.
You finish every drop.

556
00:34:06.544 --> 00:34:08.880
[footsteps approaching]

557
00:34:18.598 --> 00:34:19.807
[Caroline sighs]

558
00:34:22.185 --> 00:34:24.062
I dreamt about Father and George.

559
00:34:25.855 --> 00:34:27.732
everything that happened before we left.

560
00:34:29.817 --> 00:34:30.817
the lake.

561
00:34:34.197 --> 00:34:36.741
I believed so completely
I did the right thing.

562
00:34:37.992 --> 00:34:40.495
-You were trying to help.
-But I didn't.

563
00:34:41.788 --> 00:34:43.748
Now we're in limbo on this land.

564
00:34:44.916 --> 00:34:45.958
We're alone.

565
00:34:47.877 --> 00:34:49.545
We nearly died of the fever.

566
00:34:53.049 --> 00:34:55.343
And I'm afraid
you'll never forgive me either.

567
00:34:56.761 --> 00:34:58.763
[tender music playing]

568
00:35:06.854 --> 00:35:08.981
What'd you mean
when you said you had a way out?

569
00:35:11.067 --> 00:35:12.360
What was in that letter?

570
00:35:13.361 --> 00:35:14.612
[Caroline] Nothing.

571
00:35:16.405 --> 00:35:17.573
It doesn't matter.

572
00:35:21.536 --> 00:35:23.913
I just need you to trust me from now on.

573
00:35:25.373 --> 00:35:27.917
I need you to believe in me
the way I believe in you.

574
00:35:28.417 --> 00:35:31.045
I need you to believe
I'm strong and capable.

575
00:35:31.129 --> 00:35:34.132
I can handle whatever may come.
good or bad.

576
00:35:36.467 --> 00:35:39.345
I need you to understand
I'm in this with you.

577
00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:44.058
No more secrets.

578
00:35:56.988 --> 00:35:58.990
[White Sun singing in Osage]

579
00:36:05.913 --> 00:36:08.916
[singing continues]

580
00:36:23.222 --> 00:36:25.224
[singing continues]

581
00:36:33.149 --> 00:36:34.692
[singing continues]

582
00:36:40.531 --> 00:36:41.657
[singing stops]

583
00:36:42.408 --> 00:36:44.410
[chickens clucking]

584
00:36:54.212 --> 00:36:56.255
[in English] I've never heard a song
like that.

585
00:36:56.339 --> 00:37:00.509
It's a morning prayer.
thanking Wah'Kon-Tah. God.

586
00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:04.847
for the past. the present. and the future.

587
00:37:06.682 --> 00:37:09.101
[sighs] I haven't done it in a long time.

588
00:37:10.603 --> 00:37:11.854
-Hm.
-Why not?

589
00:37:13.773 --> 00:37:15.233
I lost my daughter

590
00:37:15.733 --> 00:37:16.901
a year ago.

591
00:37:18.152 --> 00:37:19.237
I'm sorry.

592
00:37:21.489 --> 00:37:22.949
Was her name Julia?

593
00:37:25.117 --> 00:37:26.117
Yes.

594
00:37:28.079 --> 00:37:31.415
When I came into the house the other day.
you called me Julia.

595
00:37:31.999 --> 00:37:33.376
Did I? [chuckles softly]

596
00:37:37.546 --> 00:37:39.048
Good Eagle must miss her.

597
00:37:42.134 --> 00:37:43.594
She doesn't talk about her.

598
00:37:45.096 --> 00:37:46.180
That's my fault.

599
00:37:48.266 --> 00:37:51.060
For a long time.
it made me sad to remember her.

600
00:37:51.644 --> 00:37:52.979
even to hear her name.

601
00:37:54.563 --> 00:37:55.563
But.

602
00:37:56.315 --> 00:37:58.109
for the past few weeks.

603
00:37:59.068 --> 00:38:01.529
the past few days especially.

604
00:38:02.154 --> 00:38:04.365
I've been feeling her spirit with me.

605
00:38:05.908 --> 00:38:08.077
when I see and hold her things.

606
00:38:08.911 --> 00:38:11.580
when I hear Good Eagle
laugh and play with you

607
00:38:12.415 --> 00:38:15.001
the way she used to laugh
and play with Julia.

608
00:38:20.965 --> 00:38:21.966
Ma.

609
00:38:26.429 --> 00:38:27.722
[both chuckle]

610
00:38:29.974 --> 00:38:32.518
Pa wasn't feeling strong enough.
so I came to get you myself.

611
00:38:32.601 --> 00:38:34.228
Couldn't wait another minute.

612
00:38:35.229 --> 00:38:36.314
You ready to go home?

613
00:38:36.897 --> 00:38:38.649
Okay. Run inside and get dressed.

614
00:38:40.026 --> 00:38:42.278
[footsteps running]

615
00:38:45.364 --> 00:38:47.325
Thank you for taking care of her.

616
00:38:54.498 --> 00:38:56.500
[dishes rattling]

617
00:39:00.504 --> 00:39:02.131
[water pouring]

618
00:39:02.214 --> 00:39:04.216
[fire crackling]

619
00:39:09.805 --> 00:39:10.639
[dishes clinking]

620
00:39:10.723 --> 00:39:12.725
[breathes deeply]

621
00:39:19.857 --> 00:39:21.108
You have a lovely home.

622
00:39:24.528 --> 00:39:25.905
[sighs softly]

623
00:39:30.117 --> 00:39:31.285
[White Sun] I was lucky

624
00:39:31.369 --> 00:39:33.662
to have teachers at the mission

625
00:39:34.163 --> 00:39:38.459
that encouraged my interests
in language and literature.

626
00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:41.587
Laura tells me you're a teacher.

627
00:39:42.505 --> 00:39:46.300
-Yes. before I was married.
-[White Sun] Hm.

628
00:39:46.384 --> 00:39:49.678
Now I'm just teaching the girls
at home until there's a school.

629
00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:10.658
I'm not a very patient teacher.

630
00:40:12.493 --> 00:40:16.622
I think it would be a good idea
for Good Eagle to learn with other girls.

631
00:40:17.123 --> 00:40:18.707
if you're still willing.

632
00:40:19.875 --> 00:40:22.086
There's more to education than books.

633
00:40:24.088 --> 00:40:25.131
I'd like that.

634
00:40:25.923 --> 00:40:27.967
[Laura and Good Eagle giggling]

635
00:40:30.928 --> 00:40:32.930
[Laura and Good Eagle laughing]

636
00:40:36.100 --> 00:40:37.560
[Caroline chuckles softly]

637
00:40:38.894 --> 00:40:40.729
You should get plenty of rest.

638
00:40:42.565 --> 00:40:47.153
The fever can be very hard
on both you and the baby.

639
00:40:48.195 --> 00:40:50.197
[poignant music playing]

640
00:40:53.784 --> 00:40:54.952
[sighs]

641
00:40:57.246 --> 00:40:58.414
[Jack panting]

642
00:41:01.542 --> 00:41:02.542
[footsteps approaching]

643
00:41:21.562 --> 00:41:22.771
How are you feeling?

644
00:41:23.856 --> 00:41:24.857
Much better.

645
00:41:25.733 --> 00:41:26.733
Thank you.

646
00:41:27.067 --> 00:41:29.361
I. uh. I…
I heard you saved your pa. [chuckles]

647
00:41:29.862 --> 00:41:31.530
I heard you saved my sister.

648
00:41:32.239 --> 00:41:33.908
Uh. that was. uh… that was Jack.

649
00:41:33.991 --> 00:41:35.910
Well. thanks all the same.

650
00:41:36.619 --> 00:41:38.204
Friends look out for each other.

651
00:41:40.456 --> 00:41:42.333
-[Laura] Caleb!
-[footsteps approaching]

652
00:41:42.917 --> 00:41:43.751
Caleb!

653
00:41:43.834 --> 00:41:44.960
[Jack barking]

654
00:41:46.086 --> 00:41:47.838
[both laugh]

655
00:42:07.608 --> 00:42:09.485
Hope you know how proud we are of you.

656
00:42:09.568 --> 00:42:11.237
[music fades]

657
00:42:11.320 --> 00:42:13.697
Plenty of grown-ups
wouldn't have been that brave.

658
00:42:14.907 --> 00:42:16.492
I didn't find help though.

659
00:42:18.118 --> 00:42:19.870
And Pet and Patty are gone.

660
00:42:19.954 --> 00:42:21.705
[dishes clinking]

661
00:42:22.289 --> 00:42:24.750
I must've left the stable open
when I fed them.

662
00:42:25.251 --> 00:42:26.085
Don't worry.

663
00:42:26.168 --> 00:42:29.129
They'll come back once they get
the rambling out of their systems.

664
00:42:29.213 --> 00:42:32.383
[fire crackling]

665
00:42:34.802 --> 00:42:36.720
I saw Grandma on the prairie.

666
00:42:39.139 --> 00:42:43.060
She scooped me up in her arms
and told me about the fox

667
00:42:43.143 --> 00:42:45.771
and the hens and the honeybees.

668
00:42:46.772 --> 00:42:48.399
She smelled like violets.

669
00:42:51.193 --> 00:42:52.695
I know I was dreaming.

670
00:42:54.029 --> 00:42:55.155
I just miss her.

671
00:42:57.741 --> 00:42:58.993
I miss her too.

672
00:43:03.122 --> 00:43:04.957
[Laura] Everybody came to help us.

673
00:43:05.666 --> 00:43:07.209
just like the Big Woods.

674
00:43:09.003 --> 00:43:10.337
I guess that's true.

675
00:43:14.925 --> 00:43:16.552
Should we have some music?

676
00:43:18.178 --> 00:43:20.180
[footsteps approaching]

677
00:43:29.565 --> 00:43:32.067
This is Grandpa's favorite hymn.

678
00:43:35.779 --> 00:43:38.115
-Do you remember the words?
-I remember.

679
00:43:44.622 --> 00:43:48.751
♪ Life let us cherish ♪

680
00:43:48.834 --> 00:43:53.881
♪ While yet the taper glows ♪

681
00:43:53.964 --> 00:43:58.469
♪ And the fresh flower ♪

682
00:43:58.552 --> 00:44:02.389
♪ Pluck ere it close ♪

683
00:44:02.473 --> 00:44:07.102
♪ Why are ye fond of toil and care? ♪

684
00:44:07.186 --> 00:44:12.191
♪ Why choose the rankling thorn to wear? ♪

685
00:44:12.274 --> 00:44:16.820
♪ And heedless by the lily stray ♪

686
00:44:16.904 --> 00:44:21.742
♪ Which blossoms in our way ♪

687
00:44:21.825 --> 00:44:26.497
♪ Life let us cherish ♪

688
00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:31.293
♪ While yet the taper glows ♪

689
00:44:31.377 --> 00:44:35.964
♪ And the fresh flower ♪

690
00:44:36.048 --> 00:44:39.802
♪ Pluck ere it close ♪

691
00:44:40.928 --> 00:44:41.845
[song ends]

692
00:44:41.929 --> 00:44:43.847
[closing theme music playing]

693
00:46:04.928 --> 00:46:06.930
[music ends]
